SIMPLE: roarer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roarer
<hw>Roar"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who,
or that which, roars.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A riotous
fellow; a roaring boy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lady to turn <qex>roarer</qex>, and break glasses.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>A horse subject to roaring. See
<er>Roaring</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The barn owl.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roaring</ent>⟦br⟧
